From: quark <quark@localhost>
Subject: [PATCH] win32u: Guard against NULL shared object dereference in seqlock functions

During early thread initialization (particularly winedevice service
threads), shared session object lookups can return NULL when the
server returns a zero locator for a thread whose queue or input
hasn't been created yet.

The seqlock acquire/release functions and shared_object_get_id
unconditionally dereference the object pointer, causing a page
fault at address 0x0 (seq field) or 0x8 (id field). Downstream
callers that access object->shm.input.focus crash at 0x18.

Add NULL guards to all three primitives. acquire_seqlock sets
seq=0 and returns. release_seqlock returns TRUE to break retry
loops. get_id returns 0. All callers already handle zero/invalid
ids as cache misses, so this safely degrades to a server round-trip.

Signed-off-by: quark <quark@localhost>
---
diff --git a/dlls/win32u/winstation.c b/dlls/win32u/winstation.c
index 6190e45..96cf683 100644
--- a/dlls/win32u/winstation.c
+++ b/dlls/win32u/winstation.c
@@ -81,18 +81,21 @@ static struct session_thread_data *get_session_thread_data(void)

 void shared_object_acquire_seqlock( const shared_object_t *object, UINT64 *seq )
 {
+    if (!object) { *seq = 0; return; }
     while ((*seq = ReadNoFence64( &object->seq )) & 1) YieldProcessor();
     __SHARED_READ_FENCE;
 }

 BOOL shared_object_release_seqlock( const shared_object_t *object, UINT64 seq )
 {
+    if (!object) return TRUE;
     __SHARED_READ_FENCE;
     return ReadNoFence64( &object->seq ) == seq;
 }

 static object_id_t shared_object_get_id( const shared_object_t *object )
 {
+    if (!object) return 0;
     struct object_lock lock = OBJECT_LOCK_INIT;
     do
     {
